Rating: 3
This recipe was pretty good. The only reason for not giving it the full 4 stars is because the one ingredient which differenciates it from other recipes is the thing which also managed to... well, not exactly ruin it, but it did detract from what it could have been. I was actually looking forward to the unusual addition of the cardamom but we found that its distinct and unique taste did tend to take over the other flavors a little too much. It was a little too jarring. Your mouth is all happy with pineapples, brown sugar, cake.... and then all of sudden, your tastebuds get whacked with "One of these flavors is not like the others!" I used 1.25 tsp and I think if I were to make this again (which I probably will), I will probably use just 1/4 tsp, or more likely none at all. I think the rest of the recipe is very good, and the batter is great. It's also very easy to make; cleaning the pineapple is what took the longest. Using fresh pineapples is key. BTW, we learned that the way you pick them is by plucking the pointy leaves from the top, towards the center of the fruit; they should come out easily if the fruit is ripe. Next time, I will also use more rum at the end; I couldn't even taste it. It's worth trying this recipe with the cardamom the first time you make it, but do note that it is a very strong flavor (my house smelled like it, even though it was double-bagged in Zip-Locs). Overall, a very tasty recipe but for myself, I'd probably give the cardamom a miss next time. Once is enough. One addition which worked great with the other flavors was caramel. I tried it on the leftovers and it was super. That will definitely take cardamom's place on the ingredient list next time!

